// The pipeline is an ordering domain, not the owner of any working set
// (kv_refact.md). Every command on every pipeline enters the single
// per-driver sequencer queue in program order and is linearized there; a
// pipeline names the ordering domain a command belongs to. Device-visible
// working-set mutations (`working-set.wit`) and forward submissions
// (`forward.wit`) take `borrow<pipeline>`.
interface pipeline {
    /// A run-ahead ordering domain. Commands on the same pipeline execute in
    /// deterministic submission order; different pipelines promise nothing
    /// beyond the sequencer's linearization. Creating a working set on one
    /// pipeline and firing it from another is safe by construction.
    resource pipeline {
        constructor();

        /// Graceful END OF STREAM: no further submissions; queued fires
        /// drain normally. Sequenced with the submissions (same FIFO), so
        /// calling it right after the last submit is exact: the scheduler
        /// stops awaiting the pipeline the moment its last fire dispatches
        /// into a wave. Later submits error. `close` stays legal after
        /// finish and cancels whatever is still unexecuted.
        finish: func();

        /// CANCEL the pipeline (implied by drop; close and drop mean the
        /// same thing): every queued/preparing fire is cancelled and its
        /// books deleted; already-dispatched fires are GPU-owned and run to
        /// settlement. Takes of cancelled fires error. End-of-stream is NOT
        /// close's job — that is `finish`. Touched channels are unspecified
        /// after close.
        close: func();
    }
}
